example_quotes: Medical Student: OK, have you had any changes to your sense of taste?
Patient: No, taste is fine.
Medical Student: Have your eyes been itchy?
Patient: Uhm Yeah, a little bit. I would say they have been a bit itchy.
Medical Student: And do you have any allergies to medications or like environmental allergies that might be getting worse?
Patient: Uh, no, not that I know.
Medical Student: And do you grind your teeth at all at night? or have you had, TMJ issues before?
Patient: No nothing like that.
Medical Student: OK, then how about any muscle aches or joint aches?
Patient: Uh, no.
Medical Student: I see, OK, and have you had any chest pain?
Patient: No, no chest pain.
Medical Student: OK, have you had any fevers or chills?
Patient: Uhm, I Don't think I've had a fever. I did feel some chills over the last few days, but just very brief episodes.
Patient: That was around like 5 days ago and then it turned into just a lot of congestion, like around my nose and like my throat.
Medical Student: OK, and have you had any cough or sore throat?
Patient: Uh, no. No cough or sore throat.
Medical Student: Have you had any diarrhea?
Patient: No diarrhea.
Patient: Yeah, I'm still getting some discharge and I also feel like I'm getting some dripping at the back of my throat too, especially when I wake up.
Medical Student: OK, and could you describe the discharge? Is it clear, yellow, greenish?
Patient: Uh, it's fairly clear and sometimes, like a bit white, but like, it's not like green or yellow.
Medical Student: Alright, and any lightheadedness or feeling dizzy?
Patient: No.
Patient: I also feel like I'm getting some dripping at the back of my throat too, especially when I wake up.
Medical Student: How about any shortness of breath?
Patient: Uh, not shortness of breath. Just sometimes when my nose gets like really congested, I just turn into like a mouth breather, but that's about it.
Medical Student: Did you notice any discharge from your eyes or any eye redness?
Patient: Not discharge, but yeah, maybe a little bit of redness.
Medical Student: And how has your energy been? Any fatigue?
Patient: Uhm, it's been mainly OK, just maybe sometimes difficult to get to sleep with all the all the congestion, but I don't think my energy has been affected too much, no.
Medical Student: OK, have you had any fevers or chills?
Patient: Uhm, I Don't think I've had a fever.
Medical Student: Have your eyes been itchy?
Patient: Uhm Yeah, a little bit. I would say they have been a bit itchy.
Patient: That was around like 5 days ago and then it turned into just a lot of congestion, like around my nose and like my throat.
Medical Student: OK, and have you felt that it's difficult to breathe in through either of your nostrils, like it's obstructed?

Patient: Yeah, so at night sometimes I have to like turn because one side of my nose gets difficult to breathe from and then it kind of balances out on the other side. So yeah, I do have some obstruction.
Medical Student: OK, have you had any nausea or vomiting?
Patient: Nope.
Patient: And now over the last two days I've been just feeling so much pressure around my nose and around my jaw so I've been getting a lot of pain there as well.
Medical Student: OK, and you have pain. Do you feel it in your jaw or do you feel it in the in the front of your nose?
Patient: Yes, I would say mainly over the cheeks. It can kind of go near the front of my teeth as well, so like I would say like mostly around the cheeks, jaws and up to the front of my teeth.
Patient: And now over the last two days I've been just feeling so much pressure around my nose and around my jaw...
Patient: It kind of first started with, like a runny nose.
Medical Student: OK, is your nose still running?
Patient: Yeah, I'm still getting some discharge...
Medical Student: OK, and have you had any changes to your sense of smell?
Patient: Yeah, so just in the last three days when the congestion got really bad I started losing the ability to smell.
Medical Student: OK, and have you had any cough or sore throat?
Patient: Uh, no. No cough or sore throat.
Medical Student: OK, have you had any changes to your sense of taste?
Patient: No, taste is fine.
Medical Student: OK, and over the last few weeks have you had any weight loss?
Patient: No.
Medical Student: OK, and have you had any urinary problems?
Patient: Uh, no.
Medical Student: OK, have you had any nausea or vomiting?
Patient: Nope.
Medical Student: OK, and have you had any muscle weakness?
Patient: No.
Medical Student: And you said you didn't have a cough or a sore throat, but have you had any wheezing?
Patient: No wheezing.
